05470nam a22007575i 9781474469555DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222010stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814744695557 a10.1515/97814744695552doi  a(DE-B1597)615954  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 4aB2430.D454bD444 2009eb 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a1942221 aJain, Dhruv, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDeleuze and Marx :bDeleuze Studies Volume 3: 2009 (Supplement) /cDhruv Jain. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (96 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDeleuze Studies Special Issues : DSSI00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tEditor’s Introduction -- tCapital, Crisis, Manifestos, and Finally Revolution -- tArticles -- tDeleuze, Marx and the Politicisation of Philosophy -- tThe Marx of Anti-Oedipus -- tMarx as Ally: Deleuze outside Marxism, Adjacent Marx -- tThe Fetish is Always Actual, Revolution is Always Virtual: From Noology to Noopolitics -- tMinor Marxism: An Approach to a New Political Praxis -- tPoliticising Deleuzian Thought, or, Minority’s Position within Marxism -- tReview Essay -- tAfter Utopia: Three Post-Personal Subjects Consider the Possibilities0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWritings on Deleuze and Guattari's twin volumes, Capitalism and Schizophrenia, have often focused on questions about desire, body without organs, the schizophrenic etc. There have been a few notable exceptions that have attempted to articulate and expound upon the numerous political problems that Deleuze and Guattari attempt to resolve through analyses of concepts such as de-/re-territorialization, coding and re-coding etc, however a specter is haunting Deleuze and Guattari that has yet to be explained, articulated and debated; the specter of Karl Marx. This volume attempts to analyze the relationship between Deleuze (and Guattari) and Marx and their respective works. This volume is an intervention into the fields of Deleuze Studies, Marxist and Marxian philosophy and political economy, and critiques of capitalism through an examination of the relationship between Deleuze and Marx. Themes that will be covered in this volume include hegemony and theories of imperialism, the role of philosophy in changing the world, surplus, tensions between the virtual and the potential, ideology and noology, modes of production, and the very nature of anti-capitalist politics in Deleuze's work. This volume will be of interest to people interested in Deleuze Studies who are interested in questions of politics and critiques of capitalism, Marxist theory and philosophy and people interested in political economy.Key Featuresoffers new perspectives on Deleuze's early workilluminates new connections between Deleuze's and Marx's workincludes a critical re-reading of Deleuze's workforegrounds a critique of Capitalism in Deleuze's workContributors include: Bruno Bosteels, Alberto Toscano, Jason Read, Jeremy Gilbert Simon Choat and Aidan Tynan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCapitalismxPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aCain, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoat, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJain, Dhruv, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPardi, Aldo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPellejero, Eduardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRead, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSibertin-Blanc, Guillaume, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g